What I tell my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad, and my foreign friends ask me each time, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what's going on in your country?
Here's what I tell them.
First of all, be careful not to misunderstand the 2016 elections.
Unlike some comments, the American political system was not swept away by a wave of populism.
It's true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elite.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Yet Trump missed winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been expressed differently in these states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
That said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of growing social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest best-seller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the large difference between California and Appalachia.
Research by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without a university degree are worse than those of African Americans, who historically ranked at the bottom of inequalities.
In 1999, mortality rates among those without higher education were around 30% lower than those of African Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
Furthermore, employment in the industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class whites, has strongly decreased over the last generation, to just 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring back jobs in the industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may indeed make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is not to underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his outbursts on Twitter and his scandalous contempt for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the viewers' attention, and the best way to do this is to formulate extreme statements, without caring about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his daily agenda and distract his critics.
What irritates commentators in the media and in academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his permanent campaign centered on himself to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies whom he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote evolves towards the center of politics in order to gain more support.
This is what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, proclaims that he won the popular vote and, by acting as if this were actually the case, pleases his core voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations at the Department of Defense, the State Department, and the National Security Agency, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services are situated at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps at the same time.
Fourthly, do not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends speak as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but America's founders were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government is harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes it difficult to exercise these powers.
A joke on this subject says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or for anyone else.
Inefficiency has been put to the service of liberty.
Trump's presidency is still in its early days and we cannot be certain of what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
Up to now, however, the courts, Congress and the states have seen to this balance of powers within the administration, as Madison wished.
And the permanent officials of executive branch services still carry their weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what it all means for American foreign policy and the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise than Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, complained about free-riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing global public goods: security, a stable international currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems with the international order under US leadership, the world prospers, and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can affirm with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational problems.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the US alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his members suggest that he may persist in this stance.
The power of the United States to coerce and persuade, after all, comes in large part from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common resources, is more uncertain.
Trump's Director of the Budget talks about a budget of power to coerce, with budget cuts made on the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other members of the government plead for replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral "fair and balanced" arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I wish I could reassure them on these issues.
But I can't.
